 not background-reclaimed, even if they have an old lease value.\n    81\t- The first recovery action should be supervisor-visible: write `status: \"stale\"`, preserve the previous `owner`, clear no result data, and append a `task.stale` event.\n    82\t- Reassignment or reclaim is a separate explicit action after stale marking; it should emit its own assignment or claim event instead of silently changing ownership.\n    83\t- Stale recovery must not alter board tabs, legacy thread lifecycle state, loop daemon state, or dashboard routing semantics.\n    84\t\n    85\t## Completion Result Envelope\n    86\t\n    87\tCompletion events use the same result envelope stored on the task record and sent as the `payload` of `task.completed` events:\n    88\t\n    89\t- `summary`: non-empty human-readable completion summary.\n    90\t- `outputs`: array of produced artifact references or paths.\n    91\t- `checks_run`: array of validation commands or checks performed.\n    92\t- `open_risks`: array of known residual risks, blockers, or caveats.\n    17\t## Current Slice\n    18\t\n    19\t- [ ] Analysis slice — audit the stale-lease recovery behavior note against current state constants and non-destructive constraints.\n    20\t\n    21\t## Next Handoff\n    22\t\n    23\t- Loop type just completed: execution; the stale-lease recovery behavior note was added and the Task 3 stale-recovery checkbox was closed without runtime changes.\n    24\t- Keep the mailbox cadence at 1 minute unless the user explicitly overrides it.\n    25\t- Current milestone: follow-on track — `task-plans/codex-team-mailbox-loop-task-plan.md`.\n    26\t- Next slice: run an analysis loop that verifies the stale-lease note matches `TASK_STATES`, current claimability, and the non-destructive mailbox constraints before choosing the first hardening or Task 6 follow-up slice.\n    27\t- Keep the next pass non-destructive: do not implement stale automation, change mailbox UI, broader supervisor flow, packaging rules, or board/tab semantics.\n    28\t- Decide whether the next execution slice should be hardening-first before adding any new mailbox feature behavior.\n     1\t## Loop Type\n     2\t- type: execution\n     3\t\n     4\t## What Changed\n     5\t- Added a minimal stale-lease recovery behavior note to `task-plans/codex-team-mailbox-loop-task-plan.md`.\n     6\t- Defined stale detection as explicit and manual until a later hardening slice adds automation.\n     7\t- Closed the Task 3 stale-recovery checkbox because behavior is now defined before background reclamation work.\n     8\t- No runtime behavior, UI, stale automation, packaging rules, or board/tab semantics changed.\n     9\t\n    10\t## Plan\n    11\t- Active plan: `.claude/plans/ACTIVE_PLAN.md`\n    12\t- Current milestone: follow-on track — `task-plans/codex-team-mailbox-loop-task-plan.md`\n    13\t- Bounded target: stale-lease recovery behavior note\n    14\t\n    15\t## Validation\n    16\t- `node --check src/host/team-coordination.js`\n    17\t- Result: passed; code was not changed in this pass.\n    18\t\n    19\t## Next Handoff\n    20\t- Follow `.claude/plans/ACTIVE_PLAN.md`.\n    21\t- Audit the stale-lease note against current task states, claimability, and non-destructive constraints before choosing the next hardening or Task 6 slice.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
